{{about|the Auberge in Birgu|the Auberge in Valletta which now houses the Office of the Prime Minister of Malta|Auberge de Castille}} {{use dmy dates|date=February 2014}} {{use list-defined references|date=February 2014}} {{Use British English|date=February 2014}} {{Infobox building | name = Auberge de Castille et Portugal | native_name = Berġa ta' Kastilja u Portugall | native_name_lang = mt | image = | image_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|35|53|18.2|N|14|3|24.5|E|display=inline}} | status = Intact but altered | building_type = Auberge | architectural_style = Melitan | location = [[Birgu]], [[Malta]] | address = No. 57–59, Hilda Tabone Street | start_date = | completion_date = {{circa}} 1550s | owner = Private | material = [[Limestone]] | architect = Niccolò Bellavante }}
The '''Auberge de Castille et Portugal''' ({{lang-mt|Berġa ta' Kastilja u Portugall}}) was an auberge in [[Birgu]], [[Malta]]. It was built to house knights of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of Saint John]] from the [[Langue (Knights Hospitaller)|langue]] of [[Kingdom of Castile|Castille]], [[Kingdom of León|León]] and [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portugal]].
The first Auberge de Castille, which was known as the ''vecchia alberghia di Castiglia'', was built in the 1530s. Its exact location is not known and no remains have survived of this first auberge. A second auberge was built in Barrack Front Street (now Hilda Tabone Street) during the magistracy of Grand Master [[Claude de la Sengle]]. This auberge was designed by the architect Niccolò Bellavante in the traditional Maltese style, and it housed the langue until the building of a new [[Auberge de Castille]] in [[Valletta]] in 1574. Today, the building still exists, but it was heavily altered over time, and only a [[quoin]] and some windows with Melitan [[Molding (decorative)|mouldings]] remain of the original auberge.<ref name=tom/> The building is privately owned.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zahra|first1=Lorenzo A.|title=The Spanish Langues and Auberges of the Order in Birgu|url=http://www.vittoriosahistorica.org/Leaflets/Auberge-de-Castille-Leon-et-Portugal.pdf|website=Vittoriosa Historical & Cultural Society|publisher=Veritas Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704164025/http://www.vittoriosahistorica.org/Leaflets/Auberge-de-Castille-Leon-et-Portugal.pdf|archivedate=4 July 2016}}</ref>
The building was included on the Antiquities List of 1925, together with the other auberges in Birgu.<ref>{{cite web|title=Protection of Antiquities Regulations 21st November, 1932 Government Notice 402 of 1932, as Amended by Government Notices 127 of 1935 and 338 of 1939. |url=https://www.mepa.org.mt/file.aspx?f=2627 |website=[[Malta Environment and Planning Authority]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6guMwmZDW?url=https://www.mepa.org.mt/file.aspx?f=2627 |archivedate=20 April 2016 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> It was scheduled as a Grade 1 national monument on 22 December 2009,<ref name=tom>{{cite news|title=Auberge de Castille et Portugal (Leon)|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20121127/environment/Auberge-de-Castille-et-Portugal-Leon-.447039|accessdate=1 March 2014|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=27 November 2012}}</ref> and it is also listed on the [[National Inventory of the Cultural Property of the Maltese Islands]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Auberge de Castille et Portugal (leon) |url=http://www.culturalheritage.gov.mt/filebank/inventory/01163.pdf |website=National Inventory of the Cultural Property of the Maltese Islands |accessdate=17 October 2015 |date=28 December 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208065036/http://www.culturalheritage.gov.mt/filebank/inventory/01163.pdf |archivedate=8 December 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>
==Further reading== *[http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Archivio%20storico%20di%20Malta/ASM.03(1932)1-4(Genn.-Dic)/02%20La%20Albergie%20delle%20lingue%20iberiche.pdf La Albergie delle lingue iberiche e le loro chiese nazionali / G. Darmanin Demajo. ASM. 3(1932)1-4(Genn.-Dic.70-114]
