{{Infobox song contest entry | song = {{flagicon|Ireland}} "Chance of a Lifetime" | image = | caption = | year = 1968 | country = Ireland | artist = Patrick McGuigan | as = Pat McGeegan | with = | language = English | languages = | composer = [[John Kennedy (Irish celebrity)|John Kennedy]] | lyricist = John Kennedy | conductor = [[Noel Kelehan]] | place = 4th | points = 18 | lyrics = [http://www.diggiloo.net/?1968ie from Diggiloo Thrush] | prev = If I Could Choose | prev_link = If I Could Choose | next = The Wages of Love | next_link = The Wages of Love }} '''"Chance of a Lifetime"''' was the [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]] entry in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1968]], performed in [[English language|English]] by [[Pat McGeegan]]. It was written by [[John Kennedy (Irish celebrity)|John Kennedy]].<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/tv/lucykennedy/]</ref>
The song is a ballad, with McGeegan reminiscing about the first time he saw his lover. He tells her that he thought her appearance in his life was "the chance of a lifetime", and goes on to explain that he does not want to lose such a chance.
The song was performed fourteenth on the night, following [[Norway]]'s [[Odd Børre]] with "[[Stress (Odd Børre song)|Stress]]" and preceding [[Spain]]'s [[Massiel]] with "[[La, la, la]]". At the close of voting, it had received 18 points, placing 4th in a field of 17. However, the song went to the top of the Irish singles chart, only to be knocked off a week later by [[Cliff Richard]]'s "[[Congratulations (Cliff Richard song)|Congratulations]]", which came second in the contest.
It was succeeded as [[Republic of Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest|Irish representative]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969|1969 Contest]] by [[Muriel Day]] with "[[The Wages of Love]]".
