The '''Danish Islamic Council''' ({{lang-da|Dansk Islamisk Råd}}) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[Islamic]] organization representing [[Sunni]] Muslims in Denmark.

== History ==
The Council was initiated in 2000 by the politician Hamid El-Mousti and gathered 30 associations of Muslims upon its creation.<ref>{{cite book|title=Yearbook of Muslims in Europe|publisher=BRILL|first1=Oliver|last1=Scharbrodt|first2=Samim|last2=Akgönül|first3=Ahmet|last3=Alibašić|first4=Jørgen|last4=Nielsen|first5=Egdunas|last5=Racius|date=2015|volume=7|isbn=9789004308909|page=55}}</ref>

In June 2014, the Danish Islamic Council opened the [[Grand Mosque of Copenhagen]] (officially Hamad Bin Khalifa Civilisation Center, after the Emir of Qatar [[Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani]]), the country's largest [[mosque]], and the first one with a [[minaret]]. [[Qatar]] provided $27 million to finance the construction, which led the [[Danish People's Party]] to express their concerns about potential interference of the Qataris in the Danish domestic affairs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/denmarks-first-real-mosque-opens-bankrolled-by-qatar/|title=Denmark’s first ‘real’ mosque opens, bankrolled by Qatar|website=Timesofisrael.com|date=19 June 2014|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>

In 2015, it condemned the [[2015 Copenhagen shootings]] against secular and Jewish targets, saying, "The Danish Islamic Council invites everyone in Danish society to unite in the fight against extremism and terrorism."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dr.dk/Nyheder/Indland/2015/02/15/0215003933.htm|title=Dansk Islamisk Råd: Håber gerningsmand fanges snart|publisher= Danmarks Radio |date=15 February 2015|accessdate=15 February 2015|trans-title=Danish Islamic Council: Hope the perpetrator will be caught soon|language=Danish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nyhederne.tv2.dk/krimi/2015-02-15-dansk-islamisk-raad-haaber-gerningsmand-fanges-snart|title=Dansk Islamisk Råd: Håber gerningsmand fanges snart|work=Nyhederne.tv2.dk|date=15 February 2015|accessdate=15 February 2015|trans-title=Danish Islamic Council: Hope the perpetrator will be caught soon|language=Danish}}</ref> In April 2015, the Council was in favor of the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spa.gov.sa/1347964|title=Danish Islamic Council President commends Determination Storm|website=Spa.gov.sa|date=9 April 2015|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>

The Danish Islamic Council said that the Grand Mosque of Copenhagen had chosen a moderate approach of Islam, but in a TV documentary that was aired in March 2016 on [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV 2]], a female reporter with a hidden camera recorded the imam of the mosque preaching a radical vision of Islam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gatestoneinstitute.org/7648/denmark-sharia|title=Sharia in Denmark|website=Gatesoninstitute.org|date=22 March 2016|author=Judith Bergman|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>

